HTTP/2 has a great feature called push promises. It allows you to push files from server to client pro-actively because you know the client will need it. To do this responsibly, you can send along headers that can inform the client about the ETag for example, so the client can abort the file download if it's already in cache. This is all great, but very hard to deal with Express, because I would want to use all the configured Express logic in the `push()` API that (in my case) node-spdy expose.

In other words, I would love to combine `res.sendFile()` with `res.push()` (that node-spdy exposes). This is currently pretty much impossible as far as I can see. If Express could give more access to the internals of how a file would be delivered without actually delivering it (say, provide me with headers and a file stream I could pipe to res.push) that would be a major help. Alternative solutions of course welcome :)

Example spdy-server with Express:

``` js
const fs = require('fs');
const config = require('config');
const spdy = require('spdy');
const express = require('express');

const app = express();

const options = {
    key: fs.readFileSync(config.get('server.ssl.key')),
    cert: fs.readFileSync(config.get('server.ssl.cert'))
};

const httpServer = spdy.createServer(options, app);
httpServer.listen(8080);

// a route with a push promise stream:

app.get('/index.html', function (req, res) {
    // index.html is guaranteed to need styles.css
    // if *only* my code could look like this:

    res.push('/styles.css').sendFile('./www/styles.css'));

    res.sendFile('./www/index.html');
});
```

Unfortunately:
- Express' sendFile function really sends the file directly on the response stream. I wish I could send it on the push stream.
- node-spdy doesn't make this easier because of how its `push` method works (see [push docs](https://www.npmjs.com/package/spdy#push-streams), cc @indutny).

The glue has to happen somewhere, and I'm not sure where or how. But without any changes to express and/or spdy, it seems impossible to do today.

I'm trying to track down a problem that occurs when a browser disconnects before the express app responds. I'm not sure if this is it, but I've noticed in my testing that, if a connection is dropped while several requests are occurring, the latter middlewares/routes are called with the request object of the ended call, instead of their own call.

Here's a test app to illustrate this:

```
var express = require('express')
var path = require('path')

var app = express()

// Assign a request ID to each Request
var logIdIterator = 0
app.use(function(req, res, next) {
    req.log = {
        id: ++logIdIterator,
        start: new Date().getTime()
    }
    req.log.info = function() { return req.log.id+"\t"+(new Date().getTime()-req.log.start)+"\t" }
    console.logstamp = function() {
        var args = [].slice.call(arguments)
        args.unshift(req.log.info())
        console.log.apply(this, args)
    }
    console.logstamp('Start: '+(new Date()))
    res.locals.reqid = req.log.id
    return next();
})

app.use(function(req, res, next) {
    // Catch connection closed event
    req.on("close", function(err) { console.logstamp("Closed") })
    next()
})

app.all('/', express.static(path.join(__dirname)))

app.all('/call',
    // Middleware to simulate a delay
    function time_delay(req, res, next) {
        console.logstamp('Delaying',res.locals.reqid)
        setTimeout(next, Math.random()*2000)
    },
    // Final response handling
    function response(req, res) {
        console.logstamp('Continuing',res.locals.reqid)
        res.send( { message: 'Fake Response from test delay' } )
    }
)

var server = app.listen(3000, function () { console.log("listening on port 3000\nReq\tElapsed\tStatus") })
```

To identify the Requests and Responses, I added the first middleware to increment an ID counter, and save it in both the Request & Response. I then print the Request ID in log messages.

The console.logstamp prints out the ID in the request object, plus time elapsed since the start of the request, along with the output message.

Output messages shown are:
- Start.... - The request has started
- Delaying - Artificial IO delay has started (also shows ID stored in Response)
- Continuing - Delay is done, finishing off the request (also shows ID stored in Response)
- Closed - Connection was closed before completion

